Dependency injection is a design pattern where you can pass an object's dependencies in its constructor instead of creating them yourself. In other words, you don't have to create the objects that your class needs to work, you just tell the class what it needs and it will get it for you.

For example, let's say you have a class called "Pizza" that needs a "Dough" object and a "Toppings" object to work. Instead of creating them yourself, you can pass them to the constructor and let the Pizza class handle the rest.

In code, this might look something like this:

```csharp
public class Pizza
{
    private Dough dough;
    private Toppings toppings;

    public Pizza(Dough dough, Toppings toppings)
    {
        this.dough = dough;
        this.toppings = toppings;
    }
}
```

Now when you create a Pizza object, you can pass in the Dough and Toppings objects it needs to work:

```csharp
var pizza = new Pizza(new Dough(), new Toppings());
```

Dependency injection makes it easier to test your code, because you can mock out the dependencies that your class needs. For example, if you want to test the Pizza class, you can create a Dough object that always returns the same thing and a Toppings object that always returns the same thing.

```csharp
